[{"id":"VR708806","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a horizontal bar balanced on a pivot located at the midpoint of the bar. Three downward forces are being exerted on the bar: Force F sub 1 is exerted on the left end, F sub 2 is exerted at a point located between the pivot and the right end, and Force sub 3 is exerted on the right end. A note states that the figure is not drawn to scale.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR708806.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A beam of uniform mass density can rotate freely about a support pivot located under its midpoint, as shown in the figure. Three non-zero forces, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 1\"><math alttext=\"F sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 2\"><math alttext=\"F sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 3\"><math alttext=\"F sub 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></span></span>, are exerted downward on the beam. Forces <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 1\"><math alttext=\"F sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 3\"><math alttext=\"F sub 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></span></span> are applied at either end of the beam, and force <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 2\"><math alttext=\"F sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span> is applied somewhere between the pivot and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 3\"><math alttext=\"F sub 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></span></span>. When all forces are applied the beam stays in rotational equilibrium. Which of the following claims about the force magnitudes must be correct, and what reasoning supports the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR708806_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 1 is less than F sub 2\"><math alttext=\"F sub 1 is less than F sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span>, because <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 1\"><math alttext=\"F sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span> has a longer lever arm than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 2\"><math alttext=\"F sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span>, so it must be smaller in order to contribute a torque of equal magnitude.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 1 is less than F sub 2\"><math alttext=\"F sub 1 is less than F sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span>, because <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 2\"><math alttext=\"F sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span> contributes a torque to counteract the torques from both <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 1\"><math alttext=\"F sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span> and the weight of the beam.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 3 is less than F sub 1\"><math alttext=\"F sub 3 is less than F sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, because the net force on each side of the pivot must be equal for the beam to be in rotational equilibrium.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 3 is less than F sub 1\"><math alttext=\"F sub 3 is less than F sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, because <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 1\"><math alttext=\"F sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 3\"><math alttext=\"F sub 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></span></span> are the same distance from the pivot, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 2\"><math alttext=\"F sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span> contributes a torque in the same direction as <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 3\"><math alttext=\"F sub 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></span></span>.</p>"],"answer":3}]